    <stitle>INSTRUMENTS - CLUSTER FAILURE DIAGNOSIS - Fuel Gauge</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="install" graphiccount="1">
        <title>Fuel Gauge</title>
        <figure id="f0803429" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g0803429" filename="../figg08/G0803429.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" resolution="72"/>
            <caption>Electric Fuel Gauge</caption>
        </figure>
        <para>If the
            <hotlnk xrefid="f0803429">electric fuel gauge</hotlnk>
            shows a reading and it is suspected of being in error and the steps defined in ELECTRICAL
        </para>
        <para>TEMPERATURE AND FUEL DISPLAY FAILURE do not locate the problem, the fuel level sensor must be checked. The
            fuel level sensor used is a float/resistive potentiometer type with the following output characteristics at
            different fuel levels.
        </para>
        <specpara>
            <important>
                <para>Before checking the fuel gauge, be sure the vehicle has been parked long enough on a level surface
                    for the fuel to settle out, and in cold weather be sure the cab interior is warmed up.
                </para>
            </important>
        </specpara>
        <table id="t06" tblwidth="full-page" frame="all" numbered="no" view="reveal">
            <title>Sensor Output in Ohms for Tank Fuel Levels</title>
            <tgroup cols="2" align="center" charoff="50" char="c">
                <colspec colnum="1" colname="1" colwidth="1.49in"/>
                <colspec colnum="2" colname="2" colwidth="1.80in" colsep="1"/>
                <tbody valign="top">
                    <row>
                        <entry>
                            <para>Tank Fuel Levels</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>Sensor Output Ohms</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row rowsep="1">
                        <entry>
                            <para>Full</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>88 (+/-) 3</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row rowsep="1">
                        <entry>
                            <para>3/4</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>66 (+/-) 3</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row rowsep="1">
                        <entry>
                            <para>1/2</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>44 (+/-) 2</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row rowsep="1">
                        <entry>
                            <para>1/4</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>22 (+/-) 2</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row rowsep="1">
                        <entry>
                            <para>Empty</para>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            <para>1 (+/-) 1</para>
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                </tbody>
            </tgroup>
        </table>
        <para>When the sensor wire is shorted to ground, the gauge should read empty. When the sensor wire is
            disconnected, the gauge should read FULL.
        </para>
        <para>Locate the fuel sensor gauge input pin in the cluster harness. Refer to
            <hotlnk document="s08034x_22.xml" xrefid="x0803403">CLUSTER HARNESS CONNECTORS</hotlnk>. If the resistance
            reading to the fuel tank level agrees with the above listing and the gauge does not match, replace the fuel
            gauge.
        </para>
